# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ampullaviridae
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ampullaviridae/ampullaviridae] Ampullaviruses have unique morphology, with the virions being bottle-shaped with one narrow end that smoothly expands into a wider end for an overall length of about 230 nm and width of about 75 nm at the broad end.
[src:ampullaviridae/ampullaviridae] The narrow end projects beyond the viral envelope and is likely used to inject the viral DNA into host cells.
[src:ampullaviridae/ampullaviridae] The broad end possesses about 20 thin filaments, each that are regularly distributed in a ring.
[src:ampullaviridae/ampullaviridae] Inside the envelope is a funnel-shaped protein coat that houses the viral DNA.The genome of ampullaviruses is linear, double-stranded DNA that is about 23.8 kilobases in length.
[src:ampullaviridae/ampullaviridae] The genome contains an estimated 56 or 57 open reading frames that encode for at least six structural proteins.
[src:ampullaviridae/ampullaviridae] Entry into the host cell is achieved by virus attaching to the host cell.
[src:ampullaviridae/ampullaviridae] DNA-templated transcription is the method of transcription.
[src:ampullaviridae/ampullaviridae] Archaea of the genus *Acidianus* serve as the natural host.
[src:ampullaviridae/ampullaviridae] Transmission routes are passive diffusion.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Archaea were initially classified as bacteria, receiving the name archaebacteria (/ˌɑːrkibækˈtɪəriə/, in the Archaebacteria kingdom), but this term has fallen out of use.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Archaeal cells have unique properties distinguishing them from Bacteria and Eukaryota, including: cell membranes made of ether-linked lipids; metabolisms such as methanogenesis; and a unique motility structure known as an archaellum.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Archaea are further divided into multiple recognized phyla.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Classification is difficult because most have not been isolated in a laboratory and have been identified only by their gene sequences in environmental samples.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] They have not been observed to produce endospores.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Archaea are often similar to bacteria in size and shape, although a few have very different shapes, such as the flat, square cells of *Haloquadratum walsbyi*.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Despite this, archaea possess genes and several metabolic pathways that are more closely related to those of eukaryotes, notably for the enzymes involved in transcription and translation.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Other aspects of archaeal biochemistry are unique, such as their reliance on ether lipids in their cell membranes, including archaeols.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Archaea use more diverse energy sources than eukaryotes, ranging from organic compounds such as sugars, to ammonia, metal ions or even hydrogen gas.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] The salt-tolerant Halobacteria use sunlight as an energy source, and other species of archaea fix carbon (autotrophy), but unlike cyanobacteria, no known species of archaea does both.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Archaea reproduce asexually by binary fission, fragmentation, or budding; unlike bacteria, no known species of Archaea form endospores.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] The first observed archaea were extremophiles, living in extreme environments such as hot springs and salt lakes with no other organisms.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Improved molecular detection tools led to the discovery of archaea in almost every habitat, including soil, oceans, and marshlands.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Archaea are particularly numerous in the oceans, and the archaea in plankton may be one of the most abundant groups of organisms on the planet.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Archaea are a major part of Earth's life.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] They are part of the microbiota of all organisms.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] In the human microbiome, they are important in the gut, mouth, and on the skin.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Their morphological, metabolic, and geographical diversity permits them to play multiple ecological roles: carbon fixation; nitrogen cycling; organic compound turnover; and maintaining microbial symbiotic and syntrophic communities, for example.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] As of 2024, only one species of archaea has been found to be parasitic; many are mutualists or commensals, such as the methanogens (methane-producers) that inhabit the gastrointestinal tract in humans and ruminants, where their vast numbers facilitate digestion.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Methanogens are used in biogas production and sewage treatment, while biotechnology exploits enzymes from extremophile archaea that can endure high temperatures and organic solvents.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] For much of the 20th century, prokaryotes were regarded as a single group of organisms and classified based on their biochemistry, morphology and metabolism.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Microbiologists tried to classify microorganisms based on the structures of their cell walls, their shapes, and the substances they consume.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] In 1965, Emile Zuckerkandl and Linus Pauling instead proposed using the sequences of the genes in different prokaryotes to work out how they are related to each other.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] This phylogenetic approach is the main method used today.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] The first archaea to be isolated and grown in pure culture were methane-producing species in the genera Methanobacterium and Methanococcus in the 1930s and 1940s, although at the time, they were classified as bacteria.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Archaea were first classified separately from bacteria in 1977 by Carl Woese and George E.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Fox, based on their ribosomal RNA (rRNA) genes.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] (At that time only the methanogens were known).
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] They called these groups the *Urkingdoms* of Archaebacteria and Eubacteria, though other researchers treated them as kingdoms or subkingdoms.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Woese and Fox gave the first evidence for Archaebacteria as a separate "line of descent": 1. lack of peptidoglycan in their cell walls, 2. two unusual coenzymes, 3. results of 16S ribosomal RNA gene sequencing.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] To emphasize this difference, Woese, Otto Kandler and Mark Wheelis later proposed reclassifying organisms into three then thought to be natural domains known as the three-domain system: the Eukarya, the Bacteria and the Archaea, in what is now known as the Woesian Revolution.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Extreme halophilic and hyperthermophilic microbes were also included in Archaea.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] For a long time, archaea were seen as extremophiles that exist only in extreme habitats such as hot springs and salt lakes, but by the end of the 20th century, archaea had been identified in non-extreme environments as well.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Today, they are known to be a large and diverse group of organisms abundantly distributed throughout nature.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] This new appreciation of the importance and ubiquity of archaea came from using polymerase chain reaction (PCR) to detect prokaryotes from environmental samples (such as water or soil) by multiplying their ribosomal genes.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] This allows the detection and identification of organisms that have not been cultured in the laboratory.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] The classification of archaea, and of prokaryotes in general, is a rapidly moving and contentious field.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Current classification systems aim to organize archaea into groups of organisms that share structural features and common ancestors.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] These classifications rely heavily on the use of the sequence of ribosomal RNA genes to reveal relationships among organisms (molecular phylogenetics).
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Most of the culturable and well-investigated species of archaea are members of two main kingdoms, the Methanobacteriati and the Thermoproteati (formerly TACK).
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Other groups have been tentatively created, such as the peculiar species *Nanoarchaeum equitans* – discovered in 2003 and assigned its own phylum, the Nanoarchaeota (reassigned to Nanobdellota in 2023).
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] A new phylum "Korarchaeota" (now Thermoproteota) has also been proposed, containing a small group of unusual thermophilic species sharing features of both the main phyla.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Other detected species of archaea are only distantly related to any of these groups, such as the Archaeal Richmond Mine acidophilic nanoorganisms (ARMAN, comprising Micrarchaeota and Parvarchaeota), which were discovered in 2006 and are some of the smallest organisms known.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] A superphylum – "TACK" (now kingdom Thermoproteati) – which includes the Thaumarchaeota (now Nitrososphaerota), "Augarchaeota", Crenarchaeota (now Thermoproteota), and "Korarchaeota" (now Thermoproteota) was proposed in 2011 to be related to the origin of eukaryotes.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] In 2017, the newly discovered and newly named "Asgard" (now kingdom Promethearchaeati) superphylum was proposed to be more closely related to the original eukaryote and a sister group to Thermoproteati / "TACK".
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] In 2013, the superphylum "DPANN" (now kingdom Nanobdellati) was proposed to group "Nanoarchaeota", "Nanohaloarchaeota", Archaeal Richmond Mine acidophilic nanoorganisms (ARMAN, comprising "Micrarchaeota" and "Parvarchaeota"), and other similar archaea.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] This archaeal superphylum encompasses at least 10 different lineages and includes organisms with extremely small cell and genome sizes and limited metabolic capabilities.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Therefore, Nanobdellati/"DPANN" may include members obligately dependent on symbiotic interactions, and may even include novel parasites.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] However, other phylogenetic analyses found that Nanobdellati/"DPANN" does not form a monophyletic group, and that the apparent grouping is caused by long branch attraction (LBA), suggesting that all these lineages belong to Methanobacteriati.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] The classification of archaea into species is also controversial.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Ernst Mayr's species definition – a reproductively isolated group of interbreeding organisms - does not apply, as archaea reproduce only asexually.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Archaea show high levels of horizontal gene transfer between lineages.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Some researchers suggest that individuals can be grouped into species-like populations given highly similar genomes and infrequent gene transfer to/from cells with less-related genomes, as in the genus *Ferroplasma*.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] On the other hand, studies in *Halorubrum* found significant genetic transfer to/from less-related populations, limiting the criterion's applicability.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Some researchers question whether such species designations have practical meaning.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Current knowledge on genetic diversity in archaeans is fragmentary, so the total number of species cannot be estimated with any accuracy.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Estimates of the number of phyla range from 18 to 23, of which only 8 have representatives that have been cultured and studied directly.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Many of these hypothesized groups are known from a single rRNA sequence, so the level of diversity remains obscure.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] This situation is also seen in the Bacteria; many uncultured microbes present similar issues with characterization.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] The age of the Earth is about 4.54 billion years.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Scientific evidence suggests that life began on Earth at least 3.5 billion years ago.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] The earliest evidence for life on Earth is graphite found to be biogenic in 3.7-billion-year-old metasedimentary rocks discovered in Western Greenland and microbial mat fossils found in 3.48-billion-year-old sandstone discovered in Western Australia.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] In 2015, possible remains of biotic matter were found in 4.1-billion-year-old rocks in Western Australia.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Although probable prokaryotic cell fossils date to almost 3.5 billion years ago, most prokaryotes do not have distinctive morphologies, and fossil shapes cannot be used to identify them as archaea.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Instead, chemical fossils of unique lipids are more informative because such compounds do not occur in other organisms.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Some publications suggest that archaeal or eukaryotic lipid remains are present in shales dating from 2.7 billion years ago, though such data have since been questioned.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] These lipids have also been detected in even older rocks from west Greenland.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] The oldest such traces come from the Isua district, which includes Earth's oldest known sediments, formed 3.8 billion years ago.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] The archaeal lineage may be the most ancient that exists on Earth.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Woese argued that the bacteria, archaea, and eukaryotes represent separate lines of descent that diverged early on from an ancestral colony of organisms.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] One possibility is that this occurred before the evolution of cells, when the lack of a typical cell membrane allowed unrestricted lateral gene transfer, and that the common ancestors of the three domains arose by fixation of specific subsets of genes.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] It is possible that the last common ancestor of bacteria and archaea was a thermophile, which raises the possibility that lower temperatures are "extreme environments" for archaea, and organisms that live in cooler environments appeared only later.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Since archaea and bacteria are no more related to each other than they are to eukaryotes, the term *prokaryote* may suggest a false similarity between them.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] However, structural and functional similarities between lineages often occur because of shared ancestral traits or evolutionary convergence.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] These similarities are known as a *grade*, and prokaryotes are best thought of as a grade of life, characterized by such features as an absence of membrane-bound organelles.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] The following table compares some major characteristics of the three domains, to illustrate their similarities and differences.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Archaea were split off as a third domain because of the large differences in their ribosomal RNA structure.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] The particular molecule 16S rRNA is key to the production of proteins in all organisms.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Because this function is so central to life, organisms with mutations in their 16S rRNA are unlikely to survive, leading to great (but not absolute) stability in the structure of this polynucleotide over generations.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] 16S rRNA is large enough to show organism-specific variations, but still small enough to be compared quickly.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] In 1977, Carl Woese, a microbiologist studying the genetic sequences of organisms, developed a new comparison method that involved splitting the RNA into fragments that could be sorted and compared with other fragments from other organisms.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] The more similar the patterns between species, the more closely they are related.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Woese used his new rRNA comparison method to categorize and contrast different organisms.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] He compared a variety of species and happened upon a group of methanogens with rRNA vastly different from any known prokaryotes or eukaryotes.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] These methanogens were much more similar to each other than to other organisms, leading Woese to propose the new domain of Archaea.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] His experiments showed that the archaea were genetically more similar to eukaryotes than prokaryotes, even though they were more similar to prokaryotes in structure.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] This led to the conclusion that Archaea and Eukarya shared a common ancestor more recent than Eukarya and Bacteria.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] The development of the nucleus occurred after the split between Bacteria and this common ancestor.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] One property unique to archaea is the abundant use of ether-linked lipids in their cell membranes.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Ether linkages are more chemically stable than the ester linkages found in bacteria and eukarya, which may be a contributing factor to the ability of many archaea to survive in extreme environments that place heavy stress on cell membranes, such as extreme heat and salinity.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Comparative analysis of archaeal genomes has also identified several molecular conserved signature indels and signature proteins uniquely present in either all archaea or different main groups within archaea.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Another unique feature of archaea, found in no other organisms, is methanogenesis (the metabolic production of methane).
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Methanogenic archaea play a pivotal role in ecosystems with organisms that derive energy from oxidation of methane, many of which are bacteria, as they are often a major source of methane in such environments and can play a role as primary producers.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Methanogens also play a critical role in the carbon cycle, breaking down organic carbon into methane, which is also a major greenhouse gas.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] This difference in the biochemical structure of Bacteria and Archaea has been explained by researchers through evolutionary processes.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] It is theorized that both domains originated at deep sea alkaline hydrothermal vents.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] At least twice, microbes evolved lipid biosynthesis and cell wall biochemistry.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] It has been suggested that the last universal common ancestor was a non-free-living organism.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] It may have had a permeable membrane composed of bacterial simple chain amphiphiles (fatty acids), including archaeal simple chain amphiphiles (isoprenoids).
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] These stabilize fatty acid membranes in seawater; this property may have driven the divergence of bacterial and archaeal membranes, "with the later biosynthesis of phospholipids giving rise to the unique G1P and G3P headgroups of archaea and bacteria respectively.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] If so, the properties conferred by membrane isoprenoids place the lipid divide as early as the origin of life".
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] The relationships among the three domains are of central importance for understanding the origin of life.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Most of the metabolic pathways, which are the object of the majority of an organism's genes, are common between Archaea and Bacteria, while most genes involved in gene expression are common between Archaea and Eukarya.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Within prokaryotes, archaeal cell structure is most similar to that of Gram-positive bacteria, largely because both have a single lipid bilayer and usually contain a thick sacculus (exoskeleton) of varying chemical composition.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] In some phylogenetic trees based upon different gene / protein sequences of prokaryotic homologs, the archaeal homologs are more closely related to those of gram-positive bacteria.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Archaea and gram-positive bacteria also share conserved indels in a number of important proteins, such as Hsp70 and glutamine synthetase I; but the phylogeny of these genes was interpreted to reveal inter-domain gene transfer, and might not reflect the organismal relationship(s).
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] It has been proposed that the archaea evolved from Gram-positive bacteria in response to antibiotic selection pressure.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] This is suggested by the observation that archaea are resistant to a wide variety of antibiotics that are produced primarily by Gram-positive bacteria, and that these antibiotics act primarily on the genes that distinguish archaea from bacteria.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] The proposal is that the selective pressure towards resistance generated by the gram-positive antibiotics was eventually sufficient to cause extensive changes in many of the antibiotics' target genes, and that these strains represented the common ancestors of present-day Archaea.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] This proposal is also supported by other work investigating protein structural relationships and studies that suggest that gram-positive bacteria may constitute the earliest branching lineages within the prokaryotes.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] The evolutionary relationship between archaea and eukaryotes remains unclear.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Aside from the similarities in cell structure and function that are discussed below, many genetic trees group the two.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] The standard hypothesis states that the ancestor of the eukaryotes diverged early from the Archaea, and that eukaryotes arose through symbiogenesis, the fusion of an archaean and a eubacterium, which formed the mitochondria; this hypothesis explains the genetic similarities between the groups.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] The eocyte hypothesis instead posits that Eukaryota emerged relatively late from the Archaea.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] A lineage of archaea discovered in 2015, *Lokiarchaeum* (of the proposed new phylum "Lokiarchaeota"), named for a hydrothermal vent called Loki's Castle in the Arctic Ocean, was found to be the most closely related to eukaryotes known at that time.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] It has been called a transitional organism between prokaryotes and eukaryotes.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Several sister phyla of "Lokiarchaeota" have since been found ("Thorarchaeota", "Odinarchaeota", "Heimdallarchaeota"), all together comprising a newly proposed supergroup "Asgard".
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Archaea range from 0.1 micrometers (μm) to over 15 μm in diameter, and commonly occur as spheres, rods, spirals or plates.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Morphologies in the Thermoproteota also include irregularly shaped lobed cells in *Sulfolobus*, needle-like filaments that are less than half a micrometer in diameter in *Thermofilum*, and almost perfectly rectangular rods in *Thermoproteus* and *Pyrobaculum*.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Archaea in the genus *Haloquadratum* such as *Haloquadratum walsbyi* are flat, square specimens that live in hypersaline pools.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] These unusual shapes are probably maintained by both their cell walls and a prokaryotic cytoskeleton.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Proteins related to the cytoskeleton components of other organisms exist in archaea, and filaments form within their cells, but in contrast with other organisms, these cellular structures are poorly understood.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] In *Thermoplasma* and *Ferroplasma* the lack of a cell wall means that the cells have irregular shapes, and can resemble amoebae.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Some species form aggregates or filaments of cells up to 200 μm long.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] These organisms can be prominent in biofilms.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Notably, aggregates of *Thermococcus coalescens* cells fuse together in culture, forming single giant cells.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Archaea in the genus *Pyrodictium* produce an elaborate multicell colony involving arrays of long, thin hollow tubes called *cannulae* that stick out from the cells' surfaces and connect them into a dense bush-like agglomeration.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] The function of these cannulae is not settled, but they may allow communication or nutrient exchange with neighbors.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Multi-species colonies exist, such as the "string-of-pearls" community that was discovered in 2001 in a German swamp.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Round whitish colonies of a novel Methanobacteriati species are spaced along thin filaments that can range up to 15 centimetres (5.9 in) long; these filaments are made of a particular bacteria species.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Archaea and bacteria have generally similar cell structure, but cell composition and organization set the archaea apart.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Like bacteria, archaea lack interior membranes and organelles.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Like bacteria, the cell membranes of archaea are usually bounded by a cell wall and they swim using one or more flagella.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Structurally, archaea are most similar to gram-positive bacteria.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Most have a single plasma membrane and cell wall, and lack a periplasmic space; the exception to this general rule is *Ignicoccus*, which possess a particularly large periplasm that contains membrane-bound vesicles and is enclosed by an outer membrane.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Most archaea (but not *Thermoplasma* and *Ferroplasma*) possess a cell wall.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] In most archaea, the wall is assembled from surface-layer proteins, which form an S-layer.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] An S-layer is a rigid array of protein molecules that cover the outside of the cell (like chain mail).
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] This layer provides both chemical and physical protection, and can prevent macromolecules from contacting the cell membrane.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Unlike bacteria, archaea lack peptidoglycan in their cell walls.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Archaeal flagella are known as archaella, that operate like bacterial flagella – their long stalks are driven by rotatory motors at the base.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] These motors are powered by a proton gradient across the membrane, but archaella are notably different in composition and development.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] The two types of flagella evolved from different ancestors.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] The bacterial flagellum shares a common ancestor with the type III secretion system, while archaeal flagella appear to have evolved from bacterial type IV pili.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] In contrast with the bacterial flagellum, which is hollow and assembled by subunits moving up the central pore to the tip of the flagella, archaeal flagella are synthesized by adding subunits at the base.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Archaeal membranes are made of different molecules from those in bacterial and eukaryotic membranes.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] In all organisms, cell membranes are made of molecules known as phospholipids.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] These molecules possess both a polar part that dissolves in water (the phosphate "head"), and a "greasy" non-polar part that does not (the lipid tail).
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] These dissimilar parts are connected by a glycerol moiety.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] In water, phospholipids cluster, with the heads facing the water and the tails facing away from it.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] The major structure in cell membranes is a double layer of these phospholipids, which is called a lipid bilayer.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Archaea exhibit a great variety of chemical reactions in their metabolism and use many sources of energy.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] These reactions are classified into nutritional groups, depending on energy and carbon sources.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Some archaea obtain energy from inorganic compounds such as sulfur or ammonia (they are chemotrophs).
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] These include nitrifiers, methanogens and anaerobic methane oxidisers.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] In these reactions, one compound passes electrons to another (in a redox reaction), releasing energy to fuel the cell's activities.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] One compound acts as an electron donor and one as an electron acceptor.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] The energy released is used to generate adenosine triphosphate (ATP) through chemiosmosis, the same basic process that happens in the mitochondrion of eukaryotic cells.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Other groups of archaea use sunlight as a source of energy (they are phototrophs), but oxygen–generating photosynthesis does not occur in any of these organisms.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Many basic metabolic pathways are shared among all forms of life; for example, archaea use a modified form of glycolysis (the Entner–Doudoroff pathway) and either a complete or partial citric acid cycle.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] These similarities to other organisms probably reflect both early origins in the history of life and their high level of efficiency.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Some Methanobacteriati are methanogens (archaea that produce methane as a result of metabolism) living in anaerobic environments, such as swamps.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] This form of metabolism evolved early, and it is even possible that the first free-living organism was a methanogen.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] A common reaction involves the use of carbon dioxide as an electron acceptor to oxidize hydrogen.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Methanogenesis involves a range of coenzymes that are unique to these archaea, such as coenzyme M and methanofuran.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Other organic compounds such as alcohols, acetic acid or formic acid are used as alternative electron acceptors by methanogens.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] These reactions are common in gut-dwelling archaea.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Acetic acid is also broken down into methane and carbon dioxide directly, by *acetotrophic* archaea.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] These acetotrophs are archaea in the order Methanosarcinales, and are a major part of the communities of microorganisms that produce biogas.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Other archaea use CO 2 in the atmosphere as a source of carbon, in a process called carbon fixation (they are autotrophs).
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] This process involves either a highly modified form of the Calvin cycle or another metabolic pathway called the 3-hydroxypropionate / 4-hydroxybutyrate cycle.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] The Thermoproteota also use the reverse Krebs cycle while the Methanobacteriati also use the reductive acetyl-CoA pathway.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Carbon fixation is powered by inorganic energy sources.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] No known archaea carry out photosynthesis.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Archaeal energy sources are extremely diverse, and range from the oxidation of ammonia by the Nitrosopumilales to the oxidation of hydrogen sulfide or elemental sulfur by species of *Sulfolobus*, using either oxygen or metal ions as electron acceptors.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Phototrophic archaea use light to produce chemical energy in the form of ATP.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] In the Halobacteria, light-activated ion pumps like bacteriorhodopsin and halorhodopsin generate ion gradients by pumping ions out of and into the cell across the plasma membrane.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] The energy stored in these electrochemical gradients is then converted into ATP by ATP synthase.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] This process is a form of photophosphorylation.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] The ability of these light-driven pumps to move ions across membranes depends on light-driven changes in the structure of a retinol cofactor buried in the center of the protein.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Archaea usually have a single circular chromosome, but many euryarchaea have been shown to bear multiple copies of this chromosome.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] The largest known archaeal genome as of 2002 was 5,751,492 base pairs in *Methanosarcina acetivorans*.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] The tiny 490,885 base-pair genome of *Nanoarchaeum equitans* is one-tenth of this size and the smallest archaeal genome known; it is estimated to contain only 537 protein-encoding genes.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Smaller independent pieces of DNA, called *plasmids*, are also found in archaea.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Plasmids may be transferred between cells by physical contact, in a process that may be similar to bacterial conjugation.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Archaea are genetically distinct from bacteria and eukaryotes, with up to 15% of the proteins encoded by any one archaeal genome being unique to the domain, although most of these unique genes have no known function.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Of the remainder of the unique proteins that have an identified function, most belong to the Methanobacteriati and are involved in methanogenesis.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] The proteins that archaea, bacteria and eukaryotes share form a common core of cell function, relating mostly to transcription, translation, and nucleotide metabolism.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Other characteristic archaeal features are the organization of genes of related function – such as enzymes that catalyze steps in the same metabolic pathway into novel operons, and large differences in tRNA genes and their aminoacyl tRNA synthetases.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Transcription in archaea more closely resembles eukaryotic than bacterial transcription, with the archaeal RNA polymerase being very close to its equivalent in eukaryotes, while archaeal translation shows signs of both bacterial and eukaryotic equivalents.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Post-transcriptional modification is simpler than in eukaryotes, since most archaeal genes lack introns, although there are many introns in their transfer RNA and ribosomal RNA genes, and introns may occur in a few protein-encoding genes.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] When the hyperthermophilic archaea *Sulfolobus solfataricus* and *Sulfolobus acidocaldarius* are exposed to DNA-damaging UV irradiation or to the agents bleomycin or mitomycin C, species-specific cellular aggregation is induced.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Aggregation in *S. solfataricus* could not be induced by other physical stressors, such as pH or temperature shift, suggesting that aggregation is induced specifically by DNA damage.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Ajon et al. showed that UV-induced cellular aggregation mediates chromosomal marker exchange with high frequency in *S. acidocaldarius*.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Recombination rates exceeded those of uninduced cultures by up to three orders of magnitude.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Frols et al. and Ajon et al. hypothesized that cellular aggregation enhances species-specific DNA transfer between *Sulfolobus* cells in order to provide increased repair of damaged DNA by means of homologous recombination.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] This response may be a primitive form of sexual interaction similar to the more well-studied bacterial transformation systems that are also associated with species-specific DNA transfer between cells leading to homologous recombinational repair of DNA damage.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Archaea are the target of a number of viruses in a diverse virosphere distinct from bacterial and eukaryotic viruses.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] They have been organized into 15–18 DNA-based families so far, but multiple species remain un-isolated and await classification.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] These families can be informally divided into two groups: archaea-specific and cosmopolitan.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Archaeal-specific viruses target only archaean species and currently include 12 families.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Numerous unique, previously unidentified viral structures have been observed in this group, including: bottle-shaped, spindle-shaped, coil-shaped, and droplet-shaped viruses.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] While the reproductive cycles and genomic mechanisms of archaea-specific species may be similar to other viruses, they bear unique characteristics that were specifically developed due to the morphology of host cells they infect.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Their virus release mechanisms differ from that of other phages.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Bacteriophages generally undergo either lytic pathways, lysogenic pathways, or (rarely) a mix of the two.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Most archaea-specific viral strains maintain a stable, somewhat lysogenic, relationship with their hosts – appearing as a chronic infection.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] This involves the gradual, and continuous, production and release of virions without killing the host cell.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Prangishyili (2013) noted that it has been hypothesized that tailed archaeal phages originated from bacteriophages capable of infecting haloarchaeal species.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] If the hypothesis is correct, it can be concluded that other double-stranded DNA viruses that make up the rest of the archaea-specific group are their own unique group in the global viral community.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] (2018) states that the high levels of horizontal gene transfer, rapid mutation rates in viral genomes, and lack of universal gene sequences have led researchers to perceive the evolutionary pathway of archaeal viruses as a network.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] The lack of similarities among phylogenetic markers in this network and the global virosphere, as well as external linkages to non-viral elements, may suggest that some species of archaea specific viruses evolved from non-viral mobile genetic elements (MGE).
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] These viruses have been studied in most detail in thermophilics, particularly the orders Sulfolobales and Thermoproteales.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Two groups of single-stranded DNA viruses that infect archaea have been recently isolated.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] One group is exemplified by the *Halorubrum pleomorphic virus 1* (*Pleolipoviridae*) infecting halophilic archaea, and the other one by the *Aeropyrum coil-shaped virus* (*Spiraviridae*) infecting a hyperthermophilic (optimal growth at 90–95 °C) host.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Notably, the latter virus has the largest currently reported ssDNA genome.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Defenses against these viruses may involve RNA interference from repetitive DNA sequences that are related to the genes of the viruses.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Archaea reproduce asexually by binary or multiple fission, fragmentation, or budding; mitosis and meiosis do not occur, so if a species of archaea exists in more than one form, all have the same genetic material.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Cell division is controlled in a cell cycle; after the cell's chromosome is replicated and the two daughter chromosomes separate, the cell divides.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] In the genus *Sulfolobus*, the cycle has characteristics that are similar to both bacterial and eukaryotic systems.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] The chromosomes replicate from multiple starting points (origins of replication) using DNA polymerases that resemble the equivalent eukaryotic enzymes.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] In Methanobacteriati the cell division protein FtsZ, which forms a contracting ring around the cell, and the components of the septum that is constructed across the center of the cell, are similar to their bacterial equivalents.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] In cren- and thaumarchaea, the cell division machinery Cdv fulfills a similar role.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] This machinery is related to the eukaryotic ESCRT-III machinery which, while best known for its role in cell sorting, also has been seen to fulfill a role in separation between divided cell, suggesting an ancestral role in cell division.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Both bacteria and eukaryotes, but not archaea, make spores.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Quorum sensing was originally thought to not exist in Archaea, but recent studies have shown evidence of some species being able to perform cross-talk through quorum sensing.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Other studies have shown syntrophic interactions between archaea and bacteria during biofilm growth.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Although research is limited in archaeal quorum sensing, some studies have uncovered LuxR proteins in archaeal species, displaying similarities with bacteria LuxR, and ultimately allowing for the detection of small molecules that are used in high density communication.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Similarly to bacteria, Archaea LuxR solos have shown to bind to AHLs (lactones) and non-AHLs ligans, which is a large part in performing intraspecies, interspecies, and interkingdom communication through quorum sensing.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Archaea are known to form biofilms, a common strategy among microorganisms.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Quorum sensing is thought to play a role in Archaeal biofilm formation, but less is known about Archaeal quorum sensing than Bacterial quorum sensing.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Some Archaea have been observed to form biofilms when the pH is a specific value, without necessarily relying on quorum sensing for instance.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] These biofilms are sessile communities of micro-organisms (they can contain multiple different species) that produce extracellular polymeric substances, which are used to create a matrix, within which the micro-organisms can grow.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Biofilms are beneficial as they: protect organisms from abiotic stresses; facilitate horizontal gene transfer; and enable syntropy to take place.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Biofilm formation has a number of stages: attachment; micro-colony formation; maturation; and dispersal.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] During the attachment phase the Archaea are reversibly attached to a surface by type-4 pili and archaella.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Some Archaea possess other structures involved in attachment such as hami; fimbriae; or cannulae.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] During the micro colony phase, the extracellular polymeric substance matrix is produced, and numerous archaea have been observed to produce pills and nanowires between cells.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] During the maturation phase the matrix takes on a sophisticated architecture, such as including pathways for waste to exit the biofilms.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Different archaea have been observed to produce biofilms with different architectures.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p01] Finally, dispersal can take place, where cells begin to leave the biofilm, this process has been observed in Archaea but the mechanisms behind it are not understood.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] Archaea exist in a broad range of habitats, are recognized as a major part of global ecosystems, and may represent about 20% of microbial cells in the oceans as well as a large number of cells in sea floor sediment.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] However, the first-discovered archaeans were extremophiles.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] Indeed, some archaea survive high temperatures, often above 100 °C (212 °F), as found in geysers, black smokers, and oil wells.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] Other common habitats include very cold habitats and highly saline, acidic, or alkaline water, but archaea include mesophiles that grow in mild conditions, in swamps and marshland, sewage, the oceans, the intestinal tract of animals, and soils.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] Similar to PGPR, Archaea are considered a source of plant growth promotion as well.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] Extremophile archaea are members of four main physiological groups.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] These are the halophiles, thermophiles, alkaliphiles, and acidophiles.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] These groups are not comprehensive or phylum-specific, nor are they mutually exclusive, since some archaea belong to several groups.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] Nonetheless, they are a useful starting point for classification.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] Halophiles, including the genus *Halobacterium*, live in extremely saline environments such as salt lakes and outnumber their bacterial counterparts at salinities greater than 20–25%.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] Thermophiles grow best at temperatures above 45 °C (113 °F), in places such as hot springs; *hyperthermophilic* archaea grow optimally at temperatures greater than 80 °C (176 °F).
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] The archaeal *Methanopyrus kandleri* Strain 116 can even reproduce at 122 °C (252 °F), the highest recorded temperature of any organism.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] Other archaea exist in very acidic or alkaline conditions.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] For example, one of the most extreme archaean acidophiles is *Picrophilus torridus*, which grows at pH 0, which is equivalent to thriving in 1.2 molar sulfuric acid.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] This resistance to extreme environments has made archaea the focus of speculation about the possible properties of extraterrestrial life.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] Some extremophile habitats are not dissimilar to those on Mars, leading to the suggestion that viable microbes could be transferred between planets in meteorites.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] Recently, several studies have shown that archaea exist not only in mesophilic and thermophilic environments but are also present, sometimes in high numbers, at low temperatures as well.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] For example, archaea are common in cold oceanic environments such as polar seas.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] Even more significant are the large numbers of archaea found throughout the world's oceans in non-extreme habitats among the plankton community (as part of the picoplankton).
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] Although these archaea can be present in extremely high numbers (up to 40% of the microbial biomass), almost none of these species have been isolated and studied in pure culture.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] Consequently, our understanding of the role of archaea in ocean ecology is rudimentary, so their full influence on global biogeochemical cycles remains largely unexplored.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] Some marine Thermoproteota are capable of nitrification, suggesting these organisms may affect the oceanic nitrogen cycle, although these oceanic Thermoproteota may also use other sources of energy.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] Vast numbers of archaea are also found in the sediments that cover the sea floor, with these organisms making up at least 12.8%, and in many places, the majority of living cells at depths over 1 meter below the ocean bottom.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] Archaea recycle elements such as carbon, nitrogen, and sulfur through their various habitats.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] Archaea carry out many steps in the nitrogen cycle.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] This includes both reactions that remove nitrogen from ecosystems (such as nitrate-based respiration and denitrification) as well as processes that introduce nitrogen (such as nitrate assimilation and nitrogen fixation).
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] Researchers recently discovered archaeal involvement in ammonia oxidation reactions.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] These reactions are particularly important in the oceans.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] The archaea also appear crucial for ammonia oxidation in soils.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] They produce nitrite, which other microbes then oxidize to nitrate.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] Plants and other organisms consume the latter.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] In the carbon cycle, methanogen archaea remove hydrogen and play an important role in the decay of organic matter by the populations of microorganisms that act as decomposers in anaerobic ecosystems, such as sediments, marshes, and sewage-treatment works.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] The well-characterized interactions between archaea and other organisms are either mutual or commensal.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] Mutualism is an interaction between individuals of different species that results in positive (beneficial) effects on per capita reproduction and/or survival of the interacting populations.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] One well-understood example of mutualism is the interaction between protozoa and methanogenic archaea in the digestive tracts of animals that digest cellulose, such as ruminants and termites.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] In these anaerobic environments, protozoa break down plant cellulose to obtain energy.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] This process releases hydrogen as a waste product, but high levels of hydrogen reduce energy production.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] When methanogens convert hydrogen to methane, protozoa benefit from more energy.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] In anaerobic protozoa, such as *Plagiopyla frontata*, *Trimyema*, *Heterometopus* and *Metopus contortus*, archaea reside inside the protozoa and consume hydrogen produced in their hydrogenosomes.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] Archaea associate with larger organisms, too.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] For example, the marine archaean *Cenarchaeum symbiosum* is an endosymbiont of the sponge *Axinella mexicana*.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] Some archaea are commensals, benefiting from an association without helping or harming the other organism.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] For example, the methanogen *Methanobrevibacter smithii* is by far the most common archaean in the human flora, making up about one in ten of the prokaryotes in the human gut.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] In termites and in humans, these methanogens may in fact be mutualists, interacting with other microbes in the gut to aid digestion.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] Archaean communities associate with a range of other organisms, such as on the surface of corals, and in the region of soil that surrounds plant roots (the rhizosphere).
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] Although Archaea do not have a historical reputation of being pathogens, Archaea are often found with similar genomes to more common pathogens like *E. coli,* showing metabolic links and evolutionary history with today's pathogens.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] Archaea have been inconsistently detected in clinical studies because of the lack of categorization of Archaea into more specific species.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] The reduced genome of *Candidatus* Sukunaarchaeum mirabile suggests it is a specialized parasite highly dependant on its dinoflagellate host.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] Extremophile archaea, particularly those resistant either to heat or to extremes of acidity and alkalinity, are a source of enzymes that function under these harsh conditions.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] For example, thermostable DNA polymerases, such as the Pfu DNA polymerase from *Pyrococcus furiosus*, revolutionized molecular biology by allowing the polymerase chain reaction to be used in research as a simple and rapid technique for cloning DNA.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] In industry, amylases, galactosidases and pullulanases in other species of *Pyrococcus* that function at over 100 °C (212 °F) allow food processing at high temperatures, such as the production of low lactose milk and whey.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] Enzymes from these thermophilic archaea also tend to be very stable in organic solvents, allowing their use in environmentally friendly processes in green chemistry that synthesize organic compounds.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] This stability makes them easier to use in structural biology.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] Consequently, the counterparts of bacterial or eukaryotic enzymes from extremophile archaea are often used in structural studies.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] In contrast with the range of applications of archaean enzymes, the use of the organisms themselves in biotechnology is less developed.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] Methanogenic archaea are a vital part of sewage treatment, since they are part of the community of microorganisms that carry out anaerobic digestion and produce biogas.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] In mineral processing, acidophilic archaea display promise for the extraction of metals from ores, including gold, cobalt and copper.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] Archaea host a new class of potentially useful antibiotics.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] A few of these archaeocins have been characterized, but hundreds more are believed to exist, especially within Halobacteria and *Sulfolobus*.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] These compounds differ in structure from bacterial antibiotics, so they may have novel modes of action.
[src:ampullaviridae/archaea-p02] In addition, they may allow the creation of new selectable markers for use in archaeal molecular biology.
[src:ampullaviridae/bottle] A **bottle** is a narrow-necked container made of an impermeable material (such as glass, pottery, porcelain, plastic or aluminium) in various shapes and sizes that stores and transports liquids.
[src:ampullaviridae/bottle] Its mouth, at the bottling line, can be sealed with an internal stopper, an external bottle cap, a closure, or induction sealing.
[src:ampullaviridae/bottle] From the English word *bottle* derives from an Old French word *boteille*, from vulgar Latin *butticula*, from late Latin *buttis* ("cask"), a latinisation of the Greek βοῦττις (*bouttis*) ("vessel").
[src:ampullaviridae/bottle] The glass bottle represented an important development in the history of wine, because, when combined with a high-quality stopper such as a cork, it allowed long-term aging of wine.
[src:ampullaviridae/bottle] Glass has all the qualities required for long-term storage.
[src:ampullaviridae/bottle] It eventually gave rise to "château bottling", the practice where an estate's wine is put in a bottle at the source, rather than by a merchant.
[src:ampullaviridae/bottle] Prior to this, wine used to be sold by the barrel (and before that, the amphora) and put into bottles only at the merchant's shop, if at all.
[src:ampullaviridae/bottle] This left large and often abused opportunities for fraud and adulteration, as consumers had to trust the merchant as to the contents.
[src:ampullaviridae/bottle] It is thought that most wine consumed outside of wine-producing regions had been tampered with in some way.
[src:ampullaviridae/bottle] Also, not all merchants were careful to avoid oxidation or contamination while bottling, leading to large bottle variation.
[src:ampullaviridae/bottle] Particularly in the case of port, certain conscientious merchants' bottling of old ports fetch higher prices even today.
[src:ampullaviridae/bottle] To avoid these problems, most fine wine is bottled at the place of production (including all port, since 1974).
[src:ampullaviridae/bottle] There are many sizes and shapes of bottles used for wine.
[src:ampullaviridae/bottle] In 1872, British soft drink makers Hiram Codd of Camberwell, London, designed and patented a bottle designed specifically for carbonated drinks.
[src:ampullaviridae/bottle] The **Codd-neck bottle** was designed and manufactured to enclose a marble and a rubber washer/gasket in the neck.
[src:ampullaviridae/bottle] The bottles were filled upside down, and pressure of the gas in the bottle forced the marble against the washer, sealing in the carbonation.
[src:ampullaviridae/bottle] The bottle was pinched into a special shape, as can be seen in the photo to the left, to provide a chamber into which the marble was pushed to open the bottle.
[src:ampullaviridae/bottle] This prevented the marble from blocking the neck as the drink was poured.
[src:ampullaviridae/bottle] Soon after its introduction, the bottle became extremely popular with the soft drink and brewing industries, mainly in Europe, Asia and Australasia, though some alcohol drinkers disdained the use of the bottle.
[src:ampullaviridae/bottle] One etymology of the term *codswallop* originates from beer sold in Codd bottles, though this is generally dismissed as a folk etymology.
[src:ampullaviridae/bottle] The bottles were regularly produced for many decades, but gradually declined in usage.
[src:ampullaviridae/bottle] Since children smashed the bottles to retrieve the marbles, they are relatively scarce and have become collector items; particularly in the UK.
[src:ampullaviridae/bottle] A cobalt-coloured Codd bottle today fetches hundreds of British pounds at auction.
[src:ampullaviridae/bottle] The Codd-neck design is still used for the Japanese soft drink Ramune and in the Indian drink called Banta.
[src:ampullaviridae/bottle] The plastic is strain oriented in the stretch blow molding manufacturing process.
[src:ampullaviridae/bottle] Plastic bottles are typically used to store liquids such as water, soft drinks, motor oil, cooking oil, medicine, shampoo, milk, and ink.
[src:ampullaviridae/bottle] The size ranges from very small sample bottles to very large carboys.
[src:ampullaviridae/bottle] The main advantages of plastic bottles over glass are their superior resistance to breakage, in both production and transportation, as well as their light weight and low cost of production.
[src:ampullaviridae/bottle] Disadvantages include widespread plastic pollution.
[src:ampullaviridae/bottle] An **aluminium bottle** is a bottle made of aluminium (or aluminum, outside of British English).
[src:ampullaviridae/bottle] In some countries, it is also called a "bottlecan".
[src:ampullaviridae/bottle] It usually holds beer, soft drinks or wine.
[src:ampullaviridae/bottle] A **hot water bottle** is a bottle filled with hot water used to provide warmth.
[src:ampullaviridae/bottle] It can be made from various materials, most commonly rubber, but has historically been made from harder materials such as metal, glass, earthenware, or wood.
[src:ampullaviridae/bottle] Bottles are often recycled according to the SPI recycling code for the material.
[src:ampullaviridae/catalogue-of-life] The **Catalogue of Life** (**CoL**) is an online database that provides an index of known species of animals, plants, fungi, and microorganisms.
[src:ampullaviridae/catalogue-of-life] It was created in 2001 as a partnership between the global Species 2000 and the American Integrated Taxonomic Information System.
[src:ampullaviridae/catalogue-of-life] The Catalogue is used by research scientists, citizen scientists, educators, and policy makers.
[src:ampullaviridae/catalogue-of-life] The Catalogue is also used by the Biodiversity Heritage Library, the Barcode of Life Data System, *Encyclopedia of Life*, and the Global Biodiversity Information Facility.
[src:ampullaviridae/catalogue-of-life] The Catalogue currently compiles data from 165 peer-reviewed taxonomic databases that are maintained by specialist institutions around the world.
[src:ampullaviridae/catalogue-of-life] As of September 2022, the COL Checklist lists 2,067,951 of the world's 2.2m extant species known to taxonomists on the planet at present time.
[src:ampullaviridae/catalogue-of-life] The Catalogue of Life employs a simple data structure to provide information on synonymy, grouping within a taxonomic hierarchy, common names, distribution and ecological environment.
[src:ampullaviridae/catalogue-of-life] It provides a dynamic edition, which is updated monthly (and in which data can change without tracking of those changes) and an Annual Checklist, which provides a dated, verifiable reference for the usage of names and associated data.
[src:ampullaviridae/catalogue-of-life] Development of the Catalogue of Life was funded through the Species 2000 europa (EuroCat), 4d4Life, i4Life projects in 2003–2013, and later by the Naturalis Biodiversity Center, Leiden, the Netherlands and Species Files group at Illinois Natural History Survey in Champaign-Urbana.
[src:ampullaviridae/catalogue-of-life] Current people governing the CoL, contributors, and other relevant information which changes over time, are listed on the CoL website.
[src:ampullaviridae/catalogue-of-life] Much of the use of the Catalogue is to provide a backbone taxonomy for other global data portals and biological collections.
[src:ampullaviridae/catalogue-of-life] Through the i4Life project, it has formal partnerships with Global Biodiversity Information Facility, European Nucleotide Archive, Encyclopedia of Life, European Consortium for the Barcode of Life, IUCN Red List, and Life Watch.
[src:ampullaviridae/catalogue-of-life] The public interface includes both search and browse functions as well as offering multi-lingual services.
[src:ampullaviridae/catalogue-of-life] As of 2019, the Catalogue listed 1.9 million extant and extinct species.
[src:ampullaviridae/catalogue-of-life] There are an estimated 14 million mainly unpublished species; however, this number is uncertain as there is a lack of data on the possible number of undescribed insects, nematodes, bacteria, fungi and many others.
[src:ampullaviridae/catalogue-of-life] In 2015, an expert panel presented a consensus hierarchical classification of life which included some sectors not yet represented in the published *Catalogue*.
[src:ampullaviridae/catalogue-of-life] COL+ will develop a clearinghouse covering scientific names across all life, provide a single taxonomic view, and provide an avenue for feedback from content authorities.
[src:ampullaviridae/catalogue-of-life] The CoL is developing in conjunction with the Global Species List Working Group to avoid replication and work towards an authoritative global list of species.
[src:ampullaviridae/encyclopedia-of-life] The **Encyclopedia of Life** (**EOL**) is a free, online encyclopedia intended to document all of the 1.9 million living species known to science.
[src:ampullaviridae/encyclopedia-of-life] It aggregates content to form "pages" for every known species.
[src:ampullaviridae/encyclopedia-of-life] Content is compiled from existing trusted databases which are curated by experts and it calls on the assistance of non-experts throughout the world.
[src:ampullaviridae/encyclopedia-of-life] It includes video, sound, images, graphics, information on characteristics, as well as text.
[src:ampullaviridae/encyclopedia-of-life] In addition, the Encyclopedia incorporates species-related content from the Biodiversity Heritage Library, which digitizes millions of pages of printed literature from the world's major natural history libraries.
[src:ampullaviridae/encyclopedia-of-life] The BHL digital content is indexed with the names of organisms using taxonomic indexing software developed by the Global Names project.
[src:ampullaviridae/encyclopedia-of-life] The EOL project was initially backed by a US$50 million funding commitment, led by the MacArthur Foundation and the Sloan Foundation, who provided US$20 million and US$5 million, respectively.
[src:ampullaviridae/encyclopedia-of-life] The additional US$25 million came from five cornerstone institutions—the Field Museum, Harvard University, the Marine Biological Laboratory, the Missouri Botanical Garden, and the Smithsonian Institution.
[src:ampullaviridae/encyclopedia-of-life] The project was initially led by Jim Edwards and the development team by David Patterson.
[src:ampullaviridae/encyclopedia-of-life] Today, participating institutions and individual donors continue to support EOL through financial contributions.
[src:ampullaviridae/encyclopedia-of-life] EOL went live on 26 February 2008 with 30,000 entries.
[src:ampullaviridae/encyclopedia-of-life] The site relaunched on 5 September 2011 with a redesigned interface and tools.
[src:ampullaviridae/encyclopedia-of-life] The new version – referred to as EOLv2 – was developed in response to requests from the general public, citizen scientists, educators and professional biologists for a site that was more engaging, accessible and personal.
[src:ampullaviridae/encyclopedia-of-life] EOLv2 is redesigned to enhance usability and encourage contributions and interactions among users.
[src:ampullaviridae/encyclopedia-of-life] It is also internationalized with interfaces provided for English, German, Spanish, French, Galician, Serbian, Macedonian, Arabic, Chinese, Korean and Ukrainian language speakers.
[src:ampullaviridae/encyclopedia-of-life] On 16 January 2014, *EOL* launched TraitBank, a searchable, open digital repository for organism traits, measurements, interactions and other facts for all taxa.
[src:ampullaviridae/encyclopedia-of-life] Information about many species is already available from a variety of sources, in particular about the megafauna.
[src:ampullaviridae/encyclopedia-of-life] Gathering currently available data on all 1.9 million species will take about 10 years.
[src:ampullaviridae/encyclopedia-of-life] As of September 2011, EOL had information on more than 700,000 species available, along with more than 600,000 photos and millions of pages of scanned literature.
[src:ampullaviridae/encyclopedia-of-life] The initiative relies on indexing information compiled by other efforts, including the Species 2000 and ITIS, Catalogue of Life, Fishbase and the Assembling Tree of Life project of NSF, AmphibiaWeb, Mushroom explorer, micro*scope, etc.
[src:ampullaviridae/encyclopedia-of-life] The initial focus has been on living species but will later include extinct species.
[src:ampullaviridae/encyclopedia-of-life] As the discovery of new species is expected to continue (currently at about 20,000 per year), the encyclopedia will continue to grow.
[src:ampullaviridae/encyclopedia-of-life] As taxonomy finds new ways to include species discovered by molecular techniques, the rate of new additions will increase, particularly in respect to the microbial work of (eu)bacteria, archaebacteria and viruses.
[src:ampullaviridae/encyclopedia-of-life] EOL's goal is to serve as a resource for the general public, enthusiastic amateurs, educators, students and professional scientists from around the world.
[src:ampullaviridae/encyclopedia-of-life] The Encyclopedia of Life is an aggregative environment, that collects data from other on-line data sources.
[src:ampullaviridae/encyclopedia-of-life] It provides full provenance for information through citations from its trusted databases.
[src:ampullaviridae/encyclopedia-of-life] Professional researchers publishing academic research should cite directly to the underlying data.
[src:ampullaviridae/encyclopedia-of-life] Users may not currently edit EOL's entries directly but may register for the site to join specialist expert communities to discuss relevant information, questions, possible corrections, sources, and potential updates, contribute images and sound, or volunteer for technical support services.
[src:ampullaviridae/encyclopedia-of-life] Its interface is translated at translatewiki.net.
[src:ampullaviridae/encyclopedia-of-life] EOL was made distinctive by its incorporation of 'taxonomic intelligence', a growing array of algorithms that sought to emulate the practices of taxonomists.
[src:ampullaviridae/encyclopedia-of-life] These tools included names resolution so that data entered into different databases using different names for organisms could be combined.
[src:ampullaviridae/encyclopedia-of-life] Components of hierarchical classifications systems could be used to drill-down or to expand data searches.
[src:ampullaviridae/encyclopedia-of-life] Common components of different classification schemes were used to allow users to navigate using multiple classifications and to meander among schemes.
[src:ampullaviridae/encyclopedia-of-life] This initiative overcame a major problem of many biological data bases, that of having rigid and singular classification structures that were unable to reflect the diversity of views, or evolving concepts of how names of species and other taxa should be interpreted.
[src:ampullaviridae/encyclopedia-of-life] The names management systems continue to be developed by the Global Names project.
[src:ampullaviridae/global-biodiversity-information-facility] The **Global Biodiversity Information Facility** (**GBIF**) is an international organisation that focuses on making scientific data on biodiversity available via the Internet using web services.
[src:ampullaviridae/global-biodiversity-information-facility] The data are provided by many institutions from around the world; GBIF's information architecture makes these data accessible and searchable through a single portal.
[src:ampullaviridae/global-biodiversity-information-facility] Data available through the GBIF portal are primarily distribution data on plants, animals, fungi, and microbes for the world, and scientific names data.
[src:ampullaviridae/global-biodiversity-information-facility] The mission of the GBIF is to facilitate free and open access to biodiversity data worldwide to underpin sustainable development.
[src:ampullaviridae/global-biodiversity-information-facility] GBIF strives to form informatics linkages among digital data resources from across the spectrum of biological organisation, from genes to ecosystems, and to connect these to issues important to science, society and sustainability by using georeferencing and GIS tools.
[src:ampullaviridae/global-biodiversity-information-facility] It works in partnership with other international organisations such as the Catalogue of Life partnership, Biodiversity Information Standards, the Consortium for the Barcode of Life (CBOL), the Encyclopedia of Life (EOL), and GEOSS.
[src:ampullaviridae/global-biodiversity-information-facility] The biodiversity data available through the GBIF has increased by more than 1,150% in the past decade, partially due to the participation of citizen scientists.
[src:ampullaviridae/global-biodiversity-information-facility] From 2002 to 2014, GBIF awarded a prestigious annual global award in the area of biodiversity informatics, the Ebbe Nielsen Prize, valued at €30,000.
[src:ampullaviridae/global-biodiversity-information-facility] As of 2018, the GBIF Secretariat presents two annual prizes: the GBIF Ebbe Nielsen Challenge and the Young Researchers Award.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] A **hot spring**, **thermal spring**, **hydrothermal spring**, or **geothermal spring** is a spring produced by the emergence of geothermally heated groundwater onto the surface of the Earth.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] The groundwater is heated either by shallow bodies of magma (molten rock) or by circulation through faults to hot rock deep in the Earth's crust.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] Hot spring water often contains large amounts of dissolved minerals.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] The chemistry of hot springs ranges from acid sulfate springs with a pH as low as 0.8, to alkaline chloride springs saturated with silica, to bicarbonate springs saturated with carbon dioxide and carbonate minerals.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] Some springs also contain abundant dissolved iron.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] The minerals brought to the surface in hot springs often feed communities of extremophiles, microorganisms adapted to extreme conditions, and it is possible that life on Earth had its origin in hot springs.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] Humans have made use of hot springs for bathing, relaxation, or medical therapy for thousands of years.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] However, some are hot enough that immersion can be harmful, leading to scalding and potentially death.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] There is no universally accepted definition of a hot spring.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] The related term "**warm spring**" is defined as a spring with water temperature less than a hot spring by many sources, although Pentecost et al.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] (2003) suggest that the phrase "warm spring" is not useful and should be avoided.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] In 1923, Menzier proposed that a warm spring be defined as a thermal spring where the water is below that of the human body, but above that of the mean air temperature around the spring, though this definition is contested.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] Water issuing from a hot spring is heated geothermally, that is, with heat produced from the Earth's mantle.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] In areas of high volcanic activity, magma (molten rock) may be present at shallow depths in the Earth's crust.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] Groundwater is heated by these shallow magma bodies and rises to the surface to emerge at a hot spring.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] However, even in areas that do not experience volcanic activity, the temperature of rocks within the earth increases with depth.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] The rate of temperature increase with depth is known as the geothermal gradient.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] If water percolates deeply enough into the crust, it will be heated as it comes into contact with hot rock.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] This generally takes place along faults, where shattered rock beds provide easy paths for water to circulate to greater depths.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] Much of the heat is created by decay of naturally radioactive elements.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] An estimated 45 to 90 percent of the heat escaping from the Earth originates from radioactive decay of elements mainly located in the mantle.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] The major heat-producing isotopes in the Earth are potassium-40, uranium-238, uranium-235, and thorium-232.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] In areas with no volcanic activity, this heat flows through the crust by a slow process of thermal conduction, but in volcanic areas, the heat is carried to the surface more rapidly by bodies of magma.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] A hot spring that periodically jets water and steam is called a geyser.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] In active volcanic zones such as Yellowstone National Park, magma may be present at shallow depths.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] If a hot spring is connected to a large natural cistern close to such a magma body, the magma may superheat the water in the cistern, raising its temperature above the normal boiling point.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] The water will not immediately boil, because the weight of the water column above the cistern pressurizes the cistern and suppresses boiling.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] However, as the superheated water expands, some of the water will emerge at the surface, reducing pressure in the cistern.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] This allows some of the water in the cistern to flash into steam, which forces more water out of the hot spring.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] This leads to a runaway condition in which a sizable amount of water and steam are forcibly ejected from the hot spring as the cistern is emptied.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] The cistern then refills with cooler water, and the cycle repeats.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] Geysers require both a natural cistern and an abundant source of cooler water to refill the cistern after each eruption of the geyser.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] If the water supply is less abundant, so that the water is boiled as fast as it can accumulate and only reaches the surface in the form of steam, the result is a fumarole.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] If the water is mixed with mud and clay, the result is a mud pot.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] An example of a non-volcanic warm spring is Warm Springs, Georgia (frequented for its therapeutic effects by paraplegic U.S.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] Roosevelt, who built the Little White House there).
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] Here the groundwater originates as rain and snow (meteoric water) falling on the nearby mountains, which penetrates a particular formation (Hollis Quartzite) to a depth of 3,000 feet (910 m) and is heated by the normal geothermal gradient.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] Because heated water can hold more dissolved solids than cold water, the water that issues from hot springs often has a very high mineral content, containing everything from calcium to lithium and even radium.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] The overall chemistry of hot springs varies from *alkaline chloride* to *acid sulfate* to *bicarbonate* to *iron-rich*, each of which defines an end member of a range of possible hot spring chemistries.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] Alkaline chloride hot springs are fed by hydrothermal fluids that form when groundwater containing dissolved chloride salts reacts with silicate rocks at high temperature.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] These springs have nearly neutral pH but are saturated with silica (SiO2).
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] The solubility of silica depends strongly upon temperature, so upon cooling, the silica is deposited as geyserite, a form of opal (opal-A: SiO2·nH2O).
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] This process is slow enough that geyserite is not all deposited immediately around the vent, but tends to build up a low, broad platform for some distance around the spring opening.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] Acid sulfate hot springs are fed by hydrothermal fluids rich in hydrogen sulfide (H2S), which is oxidized to form sulfuric acid, H2SO4.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] The pH of the fluids is thereby lowered to values as low as 0.8.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] The acid reacts with rock to alter it to clay minerals, oxide minerals, and a residue of silica.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] Bicarbonate hot springs are fed by hydrothermal fluids that form when carbon dioxide (CO2) and groundwater react with carbonate rocks.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] When the fluids reach the surface, CO2 is rapidly lost and carbonate minerals precipitate as travertine, so that bicarbonate hot springs tend to form high-relief structures around their openings.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] Iron-rich springs are characterized by the presence of microbial communities that produce clumps of oxidized iron from iron in the hydrothermal fluids feeding the spring.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] Some hot springs produce fluids that are intermediate in chemistry between these extremes.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] For example, mixed acid-sulfate-chloride hot springs are intermediate between acid sulfate and alkaline chloride springs and may form by mixing of acid sulfate and alkaline chloride fluids.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] They deposit geyserite, but in smaller quantities than alkaline chloride springs.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] Hot springs range in flow rate from the tiniest "seeps" to veritable rivers of hot water.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] Sometimes there is enough pressure that the water shoots upward in a geyser, or fountain.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] There are many claims in the literature about the flow rates of hot springs.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] There are many more high flow non-thermal springs than geothermal springs.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] Hot springs often host communities of microorganisms adapted to life in hot, mineral-laden water.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] These include thermophiles, which are a type of extremophile that thrives at high temperatures, between 45 and 80 °C (113 and 176 °F).
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] Further from the vent, where the water has had time to cool and precipitate part of its mineral load, conditions favor organisms adapted to less extreme conditions.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] This produces a succession of microbial communities as one moves away from the vent, which in some respects resembles the successive stages in the evolution of early life.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] For example, in a bicarbonate hot spring, the community of organisms immediately around the vent is dominated by filamentous thermophilic bacteria, such as *Aquifex* and other Aquificales, that oxidize sulfide and hydrogen to obtain energy for their life processes.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] Further from the vent, where water temperatures have dropped below 60 °C (140 °F), the surface is covered with microbial mats 1 centimetre (0.39 in) thick that are dominated by cyanobacteria, such as *Spirulina*, *Oscillatoria*, and *Synechococcus*, and green sulfur bacteria such as *Chloroflexus*.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] These organisms are all capable of photosynthesis, though green sulfur bacteria produce sulfur rather than oxygen during photosynthesis.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] Still further from the vent, where temperatures drop below 45 °C (113 °F), conditions are favorable for a complex community of microorganisms that includes *Spirulina*, *Calothrix*, diatoms and other single-celled eukaryotes, and grazing insects and protozoans.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] As temperatures drop close to those of the surroundings, higher plants appear.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] Alkali chloride hot springs show a similar succession of communities of organisms, with various thermophilic bacteria and archaea in the hottest parts of the vent.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] Acid sulfate hot springs show a somewhat different succession of microorganisms, dominated by acid-tolerant algae (such as members of Cyanidiophyceae), fungi, and diatoms.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] Iron-rich hot springs contain communities of photosynthetic organisms that oxidize reduced (ferrous) iron to oxidized (ferric) iron.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] Hot springs are a dependable source of water that provides a rich chemical environment.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] This includes reduced chemical species that microorganisms can oxidize as a source of energy.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] In contrast with "black smokers" (hydrothermal vents on the ocean floor), hot springs similar to terrestrial hydrothermal fields at Kamchatka produce fluids having suitable pH and temperature for early cells and biochemical reactions.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] Dissolved organic compounds were found in hot springs at Kamchatka .
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] Metal sulfides and silica minerals in these environments would act as photocatalysts.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] They experience cycles of wetting and drying which promote the formation of biopolymers which are then encapsulated in vesicles after rehydration.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] Solar UV exposure to the environment promotes synthesis to monomeric biomolecules.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] The ionic composition and concentration of hot springs (K, B, Zn, P, O, S, C, Mn, N, and H) are identical to the cytoplasm of modern cells and possibly to those of the LUCA or early cellular life according to phylogenomic analysis.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] For these reasons, it has been hypothesized that hot springs may be the place of origin of life on Earth.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] The evolutionary implications of the hypothesis imply a direct evolutionary pathway to land plants.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] Where continuous exposure to sunlight leads to the development of photosynthetic properties and later colonize on land and life at hydrothermal vents is suggested to be a later adaptation.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] Recent experimental studies at hot springs support this hypothesis.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] David Deamer and Bruce Damer note that these hypothesized prebiotic environments resemble Charles Darwin's imagined "warm little pond".
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] If life did not emerge at deep sea hydrothermal vents, rather at terrestrial pools, extraterrestrial quinones transported to the environment would generate redox reactions conducive to proton gradients.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] Without continuous wet-dry cycling to maintain stability of primitive proteins for membrane transport and other biological macromolecules, they would go through hydrolysis in an aquatic environment.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] Scientists discovered a 3.48 billion year old geyserite that seemingly preserved fossilized microbial life, stromatolites, and biosignatures.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] Researchers propose pyrophosphite to have been used by early cellular life for energy storage and it might have been a precursor to pyrophosphate.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] Phosphites, which are present at hot springs, would have bonded together into pyrophosphite within hot springs through wet-dry cycling.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] Like alkaline hydrothermal vents, the Hakuba Happo hot spring goes through serpentinization, suggesting methanogenic microbial life possibly originated in similar habitats.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] A problem with the hot spring hypothesis for an origin of life is that phosphate has low solubility in water.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] Pyrophosphite could have been present within protocells, however all modern life forms use pyrophosphate for energy storage.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] Kee suggests that pyrophosphate could have been utilized after the emergence of enzymes.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] Dehydrated conditions would favor phosphorylation of organic compounds and condensation of phosphate to polyphosphate.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] Carbonaceous meteors during the Late Heavy Bombardment would not have caused cratering on Earth as they would produce fragments upon atmospheric entry.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] The meteors are estimated to have been 40 to 80 meters in diameter however larger impactors would produce larger craters.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] Metabolic pathways have not yet been demonstrated at these environments, but the development of proton gradients might have been generated by redox reactions coupled to meteoric quinones or protocell growth.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] Metabolic reactions in the Wood-Ljungdahl pathway and reverse Krebs cycle have been produced in acidic conditions and thermophilic temperatures in the presence of metals which is consistent with observations of RNA mostly stable at acidic pH.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] Hot springs have been enjoyed by humans for millennia.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] Even macaques are known to have extended their northern range into Japan by making use of hot springs to protect themselves from cold stress.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] Hot spring baths (*onsen*) have been in use in Japan for at least two thousand years, traditionally for cleanliness and relaxation, but increasingly for their therapeutic value.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] 1000 BCE), baths were primarily for hygiene, but by the time of Hippocrates (ca.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] 460 BCE), hot springs were credited with healing power.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] The popularity of hot springs has fluctuated over the centuries since, but they are now popular around the world.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] In 2023 the Global Wellness Institute, a wellness industry study, estimated the global earnings of the 31,200 hot springs establishments to be over $62 billion USD.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] Because of both the folklore and the claimed medical value attributed to some hot springs, they are often popular tourist destinations, and locations for rehabilitation clinics for those with disabilities.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] However, the scientific basis for therapeutic bathing in hot springs is uncertain.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] As a result, the therapeutic effectiveness of hot spring therapy remains uncertain.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] Hot springs in volcanic areas are often at or near the boiling point.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] People have been seriously scalded and even killed by accidentally or intentionally entering these springs.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] The customs and practices observed differ depending on the hot spring.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] It is common practice that bathers should wash before entering the water so as not to contaminate the water (with/without soap).
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] In many countries, like Japan, it is required to enter the hot spring with no clothes on, including swimwear.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] Often there are different facilities or times for men and women, but mixed *onsen* do exist.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] In some countries, if it is a public hot spring, swimwear is required.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] Hot springs are used for geothermal cooking, such as boiling eggs and vegetables at Hammam Maskhoutine (Algeria), and in Japan.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] Immersing eggs into hot springs of around 67 °C (153 °F) produces *onsen tamago* (lit.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] 'hot spring egg'), which have unique texture unlike ordinary boiled eggs, with a soft-set yolk and custardy white.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] *Onsen tamago* are served in hot spring resorts throughout Japan.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] Some people drink the water from hot springs as folk remedies.
[src:ampullaviridae/hot-spring] There are hot springs in many places and on all continents of the world.
